  "school": "ICT",
  "asset": "GBPUSD",
  "timeframe": "1D",
  "market_context": "GBP/USD is trading on the daily-monthly timeframe within a defined range bounded by equal highs near 1.24500 above and a swept low near 1.18500 below. Price has just purged the range low and is forming a reversal sequence, providing higher timeframe context for fractal continuation entries.",
  "key_observation": "The same reversal sequence (purge/turtle soup → inversion → change in state of delivery) and continuation logic used on lower timeframes works fractally on the daily-monthly timeframe, allowing multiple continuation entries even after missing the initial reversal.",
  "analysis_steps": [
    "Step 1: Identify the daily-monthly range, marking equal highs near 1.24500 above and the range low near 1.18500 below.",
    "Step 2: Observe price sweeping (purging) the range low — the turtle soup that initiates the reversal sequence.",
    "Step 3: Confirm the reversal sequence with an inversion followed by a change in state of delivery to establish bullish bias.",
    "Step 4: Look for displacement higher and a retracement back into the fair value gap left by the displacement candle.",
    "Step 5: Wait for price to close over the series of down-close candles into an important level, forming a new opposing candle / order block as a continuation entry.",
    "Step 6: On the next retest of that opposing candle, also factor in volume imbalances as additional confluence for continuation.",
    "Step 7: Track price expanding higher to take the other side of the range (buy-side liquidity at the equal highs)."
  ],
  "outcome": "Price continued higher off the continuation entries and reached the opposite side of the daily-monthly range, taking the buy-side liquidity at the equal highs near 1.24500.",
  "lessons": "Reversal sequence and continuation entry concepts are fractal — they apply identically on daily-monthly timeframes. You don't need to catch the initial reversal; multiple continuation entries at fair value gaps and opposing candle closures keep you aligned with directional bias.",
